undaries philosophers set up between epistemology, ethics, and political philosophy. Knowledge, he argues, takes different forms in various social domains, and all are subject to political struggle. A critique of contemporary society must draw on many social domains of knowledge, including the arts and religion, and should recast politics as a striving for truth in the broadest sense. Proposing a new conception of truth – one that emphasizes the unity of knowledge and truth, as well as their diversity among different social domains – Zuidervaart asks what such holism and pluralism suggest about how we understand politics and society. This book proposes a new understanding of large-scale social change, challenging how most people think about knowledge and truth.Interweaving epistemology, social criticism, and political thought, Shattering Silos aims to help redirect an allegedly post-truth society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxPolitical aspects. 0aKnowledge, Theory ofxSocial aspects. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aTruthxPolitical aspects. 0aTruthfulness and falsehoodxPolitical aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aCritical Theory.  aGreek thought.  aHannah Arendt.  aHegel.  aHerman Dooyeweerd.  aInstitute for Christian Studies.  aJewish thought.  aJurgen Habermas.  aMartin Heidegger.  aMichel Foucault.  aReligious Left.  aTerrence Malick.  aTheodor Adorno.  aadministrative state.  aaesthetics.  aanalytic.  aart.  abelief.  acapitalism.  acivil society.  acontinental.  aepistemology.  aevil.  afreedom.  agood.  aholism.  ahope.  ahuman flourishing.  ainsight.  ainterdisciplinary studies.  ajustice.  aphenomenology.  aphilosophy.  apluralism.  apolitical thought.  apost-truth.  apostsecular.  apower.